<TEI.2><text><body><div1 type="alphabetic letter" n="I" org="uniform" sample="complete"><entryFree key="Iniquity" type="main" opt="n"><orth extent="full" opt="n">Iniquity,</orth> wickedness: <bibl n="shak. luc 626" default="NO" valid="yes">Lucr. 626</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. luc 626" default="NO" valid="yes">Lucr. 626</bibl> <bibl n="shak. luc 626" default="NO" valid="yes">Lucr. 626</bibl> <bibl n="shak. son 62.12" default="NO" valid="yes">Sonn. 62, 12</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. wt 4.4.694" default="NO" valid="yes">Wint. IV, 4, 694</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. h5 4.1.160" default="NO" valid="yes">H5 IV, 1, 160</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. 2h6 4.2.29" default="NO" valid="yes">H6B IV, 2, 29</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. oth 1.2.3" default="NO" valid="yes">Oth. I, 2, 3</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. oth 4.1.208" default="NO" valid="yes">IV, 1, 208</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. per 4.6.93" default="NO" valid="yes">Per. IV, 6, 93</bibl>. Abstr. pro concr.: <bibl n="shak. per 4.6.28" default="NO" valid="yes">Per. IV, 6, 28</bibl>. It was one of the names of the Vice, the established buffoon of the old Moralities: <cit><quote>which is the wiser here? Justice or I.?</quote> <bibl n="shak. mm 2.1.181" default="NO" valid="yes">Meas. II, 1, 181</bibl></cit>. <cit><quote>like the formal vice I.</quote> <bibl n="shak. r3 3.1.82" default="NO" valid="yes">R3 III, 1, 82</bibl></cit>. The same allusion perhaps in <bibl n="shak. 1h4 2.4.500" default="NO" valid="yes">H4A II, 4, 500</bibl>: <emph>that reverend vice, that grey i.</emph>
</entryFree></div1></body></text></TEI.2>